{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638912"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:01:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:01:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17749"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17749"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.67,0.06,0.03,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10463"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77903"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10463"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17749"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63381"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11019"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24427"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26715"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77903"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a severe allergic reaction after accidentally consuming nuts. He has a known history of nut allergy. He is experiencing difficulty breathing, with swelling of the face and throat, and a widespread rash. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 80/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 90% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. He has stridor and wheezing on auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of shock is he most likely experiencing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cardiogenic","Distributive","Hypovolaemic","Neurogenic","Obstructive"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is experiencing anaphylaxis, a severe allergic reaction that can lead to \u003Cstrong\u003Edistributive shock\u003C/strong\u003E. In anaphylaxis, there is widespread vasodilation and increased vascular permeability, leading to a significant drop in blood pressure and inadequate tissue perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiogenic shock\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by the heart\u0027s inability to pump effectively, often due to myocardial infarction or heart failure, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypovolaemic shock\u003C/strong\u003E results from a significant loss of blood or fluid volume, such as in severe bleeding or dehydration, which is not the primary issue in anaphylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObstructive shock\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there is a physical obstruction to blood flow, such as in pulmonary embolism or cardiac tamponade, which is not relevant in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurogenic shock\u003C/strong\u003E is a type of distributive shock caused by a loss of sympathetic tone, often due to spinal cord injury, which is not applicable here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImmediate treatment with intramuscular adrenaline is critical in managing anaphylaxis to counteract the effects of histamine and other mediators causing vasodilation and increased permeability.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anaphylaxis is a severe, life-threatening allergic reaction that can lead to distributive shock.","Distributive shock in anaphylaxis is due to widespread vasodilation and increased vascular permeability.","Immediate treatment with intramuscular adrenaline is critical in managing anaphylaxis."],"references":["Tupper J, Visser S. Anaphylaxis: A review and update. Can Fam Physician. 2010 Oct;56(10):1009-11. PMID: 20944042; PMCID: PMC2954079.","Reber LL, Hernandez JD, Galli SJ. The pathophysiology of anaphylaxis. J Allergy Clin Immunol. 2017 Aug;140(2):335-348. doi: 10.1016/j.jaci.2017.06.003. PMID: 28780941; PMCID: PMC5657389.","Alye\u015fil C, Do\u011fan N\u00d6, \u00d6zturan \u0130U, G\u00fcney S. Distributive Shock in the Emergency Department: Sepsis, Anaphylaxis, or Capillary Leak Syndrome? J Emerg Med. 2017 Jun;52(6):e229-e231. doi: 10.1016/j.jemermed.2017.01.012. Epub 2017 Feb 21. PMID: 28238385.","Brown SG. The pathophysiology of shock in anaphylaxis. Immunol Allergy Clin North Am. 2007 May;27(2):165-75, v. doi: 10.1016/j.iac.2007.03.003. PMID: 17493496."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63381"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17749"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63381"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T20:29:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T20:30:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10463"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77903"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71